{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:44:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:44:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.41,0.16,0.25,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59326"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44737"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"628"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1224"},{"type":"tags","id":"1515"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"8056"},{"type":"tags","id":"9800"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18599"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59326"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of itchy rash. She has a history of mild atopic dermatitis since childhood which has been well-controlled with using daily topical moisturisers, and she has not needed steroid cream since primary school. She takes no regular medications. Her symptoms began shortly after moving into a new sharehouse with six other housemates. She reports increased itching and redness on her arms and neck. She also notes sneezing and itchy eyes. On direct questioning, she mentions her new housemate has three cats but the cats have regular care for fleas and ticks.  The patient thinks she might have noticed similar symptoms when she stayed with her Aunty on the farm as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are erythematous, scaly patches with excoriation marks on her neck and antecubital fossae. She has bilateral conjunctival injection and clear rhinorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patch testing","Skin prick testing","Total serum IgE level","Trial of oral antihistamines","Food allergy panel"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with worsening atopic dermatitis and new onset allergic symptoms temporally related to cat exposure. The combination of skin manifestations with respiratory and ocular symptoms strongly suggests pet dander allergy as a trigger.  Allergies to cats are the most common of mammalians-origin allergy in humans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin prick testing\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing specific allergies, including pet dander. In the presence of rhinitis, asthma, atopic dermatitis, potential food reactions, it is reasonable to perform skin prick testing to determine the specific IgE allergies. Despite the presence of active eczema, skin prick testing can still be performed on uninvolved skin. It provides rapid results with minimal side effects, and can help confirm the specific allergen triggering both the cutaneous and respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatch testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions such as contact dermatitis. It would not be helpful in diagnosing immediate type I hypersensitivity reactions to pet dander.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal serum IgE level\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in patients with atopic conditions but is non-specific and does not identify the particular allergen causing symptoms. It has poor predictive value for specific allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial of oral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E might provide symptomatic relief but is not diagnostic. Identifying the specific trigger through appropriate testing is essential for long-term management. It would assist her but not aid her on the specifics of her allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFood allergy panel\u003C/strong\u003E testing would not be appropriate as the temporal relationship between symptom onset and cat exposure strongly suggests pet dander as the trigger rather than food allergies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pet allergies can exacerbate pre-existing atopic conditions including atopic dermatitis.","Skin prick testing is the gold standard for confirming pet dander allergies even in patients with atopic dermatitis."],"references":["Skin Prick Testing Guide for Diagnosis of Allergic Disease.  Allergy and Anaphylaxis Australia. 2024. Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/images/ASCIA_HP_Skin_Prick_Testing_Guide_2024.pdf","Schoos A, Nwaru B, Borres M.  Component-resolved diagnostics in pet allergy: Current perspectives and future directions. Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology. 2021: 147 (4).  Available at: https://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(21)00003-8/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44737"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-06T22:01:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-06T22:02:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59326"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understa